metadata.name: Fizz 2.0 #200
metadata.description:
Experimental Art.

This piece is inspired by a mathematical theorem known as 'Circle packing'. This algorithm aims to cram a bunch of circles into space as tightly as possible. This is a well-explored topic throughout the history of mathematics, but at the end of the day it's mathematics, it's BORING. So to make 'Fizz' a little bit thrilling and different, I wrote an algorithm that randomly draws 450 circles with totally different radiuses (range(width * 0.1, width * 0.001) to be exact) on a canvas, and checks each circle, if the randomly chosen location is a good fit for a new circle to avoid collisions.

Combined with some cool colors and gradients for both the background and the circles, this procedure is all it took to produce 'Fizz'.
Bereft of meaning, feel free to interpret it as you please.

metadata.name: Hiding in Plain Sight #83
metadata.description:
This project is a study and exploration in the fields of Abstract Expressionism and Algorithmic Art. I am trying to find a middle way between a humanistic expressive look and feel, and a computational structural foundation underneath it. First I shape and sculpt a simplex noise field to have a base structure to work with. Second I slice it up in layers where some layers are removed and others are being kept as the final sculpture. Third I draw strokes of the remaining layers and give it an expressive style. 

I have no designs for the brush strokes, it is all generated as a consequence of how the system is programmed on what to reveal and what not to reveal. There are strict ranges where the noise field stays in which give certain consistent visuals, but they are random ranges and not fixed designs. This decision gave a lot of room for interesting random strokes, as if the algo is brushing expressively.  

I have only scratched the surface of sculpting noise fields and drawing an image out of it. To think about the possibilities of algorithmically shaping structures and drawing an expressive artpiece is just mind-boggling. The project title is hinting on the potential of these artpieces, where inspiration to further develop this art domain is hiding in plain sight.

Hotkey
s - to save an image as PNG - 8000 x 5000

metadata.name: Weave #13
A Strange Loop #237
metadata.description:
[ TAP/CLICK TO ACTIVATE SOUND ]

A whiff of pattern begins to emerge. Out of disarray comes the familiar pulsation of an ordered signal. The sense of regularity strengthens and we feel it swelling towards a singularity. Heeere weeee goooo… BAM! Then off again marching back into chaos to repeat the cycle.

Proposed by cognitive scientist Douglas Hofstadter in his 1979 book “Gödel, Escher, Bach”, and further developed in his 2007 book “I Am a Strange Loop”, “Strange Loops” are Hofstadter’s attempt at explaining the mechanisms that give rise to the sensation of “I” - through hierarchical, self-referential, and at times seemingly paradoxical feedback-loops of abstraction and causality. 

—

“Who shoves whom around in the tangled megaganglion that is your brain, and who shoves whom around in ‘this teetering bulb of dread and dream’ that is mine?”

“Do dreads and dreams, hopes and griefs, ideas and beliefs, interests and doubts, infatuations and envies, memories and ambitions, bouts of nostalgia and floods of empathy, flashes of guilt and sparks of genius, play any role in the world of physical objects? Do such pure abstractions have causal powers? Can they shove massive things around, or are they just impotent fictions?” 

"In the end, we are self-perceiving, self-inventing, locked-in mirages that are little miracles of self-reference. [...] Poised midway between the unvisualizable cosmic vastness of curved spacetime and the dubious, shadowy flickerings of charged quanta, we human beings, more like rainbows and mirages than like raindrops or boulders, are unpredictable self-writing poems — vague, metaphorical, ambiguous, and sometimes exceedingly beautiful.”

- Douglas Hofstadter, “I Am a Strange Loop”, 2007

–-

metadata.name: abstraction #25
metadata.description:
Diagrams of patterns on spheres, planets, fields, and platonic solids rendered isometrically. Ink on paper (on js).

Press DOWN to save an SVG suitable for plotting (or laser etching).
Press UP to save a 2400 x 2400 png. If you need a bigger image, zoom out and refresh, the canvas will fit the window.

Physics is fundamentally idealist. We search for simple rules from which the complexities of the universe emerge. But real systems are exceptionally complex, closed-form solutions are the exception. The deeper we dive into the fundamental nature of the universe, the less clear the rules become. Are the rules we've developed fundamental, or are they empirical approximations?

metadata.name: monopole #65
metadata.description:
Physics is, above all, beautiful.

Inspired by all the things I find beautiful in physics, and the nostalgia I feel for my undergraduate days of learning about the universe. I sought here to explore what can be created with simple graphics showing simple physical systems. 

The vector field shown is the field from a collection of monopoles, such as electrons and positrons or hypothetical magnetic monopoles.

The papers and inks available are those I have on my desk.

A 2400x2400 download of the image can be generated by pressing UP, but this will take several minutes. An SVG download can be made by pressing DOWN and is suitable for plotting (or laser cutting).

metadata.name: Trouvaille #3
metadata.description:
"Trouvaille" is an abstract artwork focusing on the composition and density of elements. Each of the elements are divided and placed according to the algorithm to work in harmony with each other. The background consists of countless lines that create a halo-like state in the center. Various sizes and densities and more than 12 color palettes have been used.

Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

metadata.name: Los Osos 2422 #1076
metadata.description:
# Los Osos 2422

I was working on the next EmProps release when accidentally I opened a link to a bear utopic civilization through their existing metaverse. Or should I say "metabears"?

Enter Los Osos 2422. 

Four hundred years into the future bears live in a peaceful civilization heavily inspired by the generative art movement of our times. They are organized in districts that are sustained by bamboo, salmon, berries, and art! Los Osos are black, grizzly, panda, and polar, yet there are no distinctions between species; it's not like they were humans. 

They have different occupations but frequently bears change jobs giving birth to the most eclectic looks.

I took my sketchbook out to capture what I could and started drawing but my presence pissed them off. Ninjas, luchadores, and even a cybearpunk forced me to escape.  Is that a live gummy bear or am I just hungry? The story will continue...

-- 

Los Osos 2422 is a PFP art piece composed of 320 hand-made drawings made as an homage to the nascent generative art current fueled by Tezos blockchain technology in 2022. It features hundreds of references to artists and pieces in several generative and non-generative fields.

The project combines the assets together using a custom open-source algorithm that allows them to stack with the positioning in front and behind the character to create possibilities like shirt collars or hats, dynamic tinting to have hoodies or glasses with different colors, exceptions to give them laser eyes or a green apple in front of the face, complex set-ups to have different versions for some of the outfits, and chance control to allow precise control over the features.

--

Press 'S' on the keyboard to save it as an 1800 x 1800 pixels PNG.
